Diseñamos soluciones de comunicaciones que resuelven problemas de salud públicos.

fields.name: NURHI
fields.description: NURHI is a five year (2009 ‐2014) project funded by the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and led by the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health Center for Communication Programs (JHU•CCP) that aims to increase the use of modern family planning methods among the urban poor in Nigeria. As part of its efforts, NURHI has spent the past three years training providers in family planning counseling and provision of IUDs and implants, and improving health facility management systems.
fields.description_en: NURHI is a five year (2009 ‐2014) project funded by the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and led by the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health Center for Communication Programs (JHU•CCP) that aims to increase the use of modern family planning methods among the urban poor in Nigeria. As part of its efforts, NURHI has spent the past three years training providers in family planning counseling and provision of IUDs and implants, and improving health facility management systems.
fields.description_es: NURHI es un proyecto de cinco años (2009-2014) financiado por la Fundación Bill and Melinda Gates y dirigido por el Centro para Programas de Comunicación (CCP) de la Escuela de Salud Pública Johns Hopkins Bloomberg (JHU-CCP) que tiene como objetivo aumentar el uso de métodos modernos de planificación familiar entre las clases pobres de Nigeria. Como parte de sus esfuerzos, NURHI ha dedicado los últimos tres años a capacitar proveedores en materia de asesoramiento para la planificación familiar y a proveer DIU e implantes, y mejorar los sistemas de gestión de centros de salud.

fields.name: Ghana Behavior Change Support
fields.description:
Living the GoodLife in Ghana: Encouraging families to eat healthier, more nutritious foods.

The Ghana Behavior Change Support (BCS) project was a four-year, USAID-funded project managed by the Johns Hopkins Center for Communication Programs (CCP) in partnership with the Ministry of Health and the Ghana Health Service (GHS). The overall purpose of the project was to assist the GHS at the national, regional and district levels to support its efforts to achieve health-related millennium development goals through sustained and coherent social and behavior change communication (BCC) interventions. BCS aimed to increase demand and use of commodities and services and create positive behaviors in the areas of: Maternal Neonatal & Child Health; Family Planning; Malaria Prevention & Treatment; Nutrition; Water, Sanitation, & Hygiene.
fields.description_en:
Living the GoodLife in Ghana: Encouraging families to eat healthier, more nutritious foods.

The Ghana Behavior Change Support (BCS) project was a four-year, USAID-funded project managed by the Johns Hopkins Center for Communication Programs (CCP) in partnership with the Ministry of Health and the Ghana Health Service (GHS). The overall purpose of the project was to assist the GHS at the national, regional and district levels to support its efforts to achieve health-related millennium development goals through sustained and coherent social and behavior change communication (BCC) interventions. BCS aimed to increase demand and use of commodities and services and create positive behaviors in the areas of: Maternal Neonatal & Child Health; Family Planning; Malaria Prevention & Treatment; Nutrition; Water, Sanitation, & Hygiene.
fields.description_es:
Vivir una buena vida en Ghana: alentar a las familias a comer alimentos más sanos y nutritivos.

El proyecto Apoyo para el Cambio de Conductas en Ghana (BCS) fue un proyecto de cuatro años financiado por USAID y administrado por el Centro para Programas de Comunicación (CCP) Johns Hopkins en asociación con el Ministerio de Salud y el Servicio de Salud de Ghana (GHS). El propósito general del proyecto fue ayudar al GHS a nivel nacional, regional y de distrito, para respaldar los esfuerzos por lograr los objetivos de desarrollo del milenio a través de comunicaciones para cambiar conductas (BCC) y generar cambios sociales sostenidos y coherentes. El proyecto BCS tuvo como objetivo aumentar la demanda y el uso de productos básicos y servicios, y crear conductas positivas en las áreas de: Salud Materna, Infantil y Neonatal; Planificación familiar; Prevención y tratamiento de la malaria; Nutrición; Agua; Sanidad e Higiene.
